<subSubSection lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="16" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="14.[150,1438,1878,2011]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<taxonomicName box="[151,263,1878,1903]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ponerinae">Ponerinae</taxonomicName>
contains two tribes, 
<taxonomicName box="[505,652,1878,1903]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Platythyreini">Platythyreini</taxonomicName>
, with the single genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Roger. These" authorityYear="1863" box="[919,1049,1878,1903]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Platythyrea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[919,1049,1878,1903]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Platythyrea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName box="[1115,1210,1878,1903]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Ponerini">Ponerini</taxonomicName>
with the remaining genera. 
<taxonomicName box="[242,337,1914,1939]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Ponerini">Ponerini</taxonomicName>
is here divided into six informal genus groups based on molecular phylogenetic results (
<bibRefCitation author="Schmidt, C." pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="201 - 250" refId="ref161753" refString="Schmidt, C. (2013) Molecular phylogenetics of ponerine ants (Hymenoptera: Formicidae: Ponerinae). Zootaxa, 3647 (2), 201 - 250. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3647.2.1" type="journal article" year="2013">Schmidt, 2013</bibRefCitation>
). Firm morphological synapomorphies have not been found for all of these groups, and their relationships are still unresolved, but the monophyly of each is generally well supported by the available evidence.
</paragraph>
